 target practice at Mag\ndalena bay, which will probably oc\ncupy three days.\nThere are no\nCallao and Magdalena bay.\nwireless stations be\ntween\nThis is the longest trip of the long\nand unless news of the pas\nof the warships is brought ashore\nby some passing vessels the fleet will\nnot be heard from again until they\napproach Magdalena bay.\nThe fleet left Hampton Roads De\nroyage\nsage\ncember 16 and made its first stop in\nSouth America at Trinidad, December\n23. Five days' sailing from Callao\nwill bring Panama abeam and the ves\nsels will then be practically clear of\nCounting the long\nSouth America,\nslops made at Trinidad, Rio, Punta\nArenas and Callao, they have made\nthe circuit of South America in ap\nproxlmately 73 days.\nAdmiral Evans Improving.\nAdmiral Evans has been reported as\nsuffering from rheumatism, but Is now\nTO BE GRAND NAVAL DISPLAY\n_\nimproving.\nWhen Evans' Feet Reaches San Fran\ncisco Bay.\nWhen the battleship fleet reaches\nSan Francisco, about the middle of\nApril, Secretary Metcalf promises to\nthe people of the Pacific coast \"the\ngrandest naval display in the history\nof the country.\" Forty-five American\nfighting ships will occupy San Fran\ncisco bay. The secretary of the navy,\naboard the Yankton as his flagship,\n*111 review the fleet.\nThe ships, which include the 16 bat\nof Admiral Evans' fleet, be\nsides the West Virginia and the Ne\nbraska, the heavy 14,600-ton cruisers\nTennessee, Washington, South Dako\nta, California, Colorado and Maryland:\nthe cruisers Charleston, Milwaukee,\nSt. Louis and Albany, and the om\nplement of torpedo boats and auxiliary\nwill be anchored in the bay\n(rom Mission wharf to Hunter's point.\nRoumanla is the most Illiterate coun\nby In Europe. The last census shows\nthat In a population of about 6,000.000.\nnearly 4,000,000 neither write nor read\n._ U\nPale,\nm.\nNervous\nThen your blood must be in\nvery bad condition. You\ncertainly know what to take,\nthen take it Ayer's Sarsa\nParilla. If you doubt, then\nconsult your doctor. We know\nw hat he will say about this\ngrand old family medicine.\nuk?h. jf tint question yonr doctor would\n\u00abut d\u00fbf\u00ee J\u00bb;i r bowels regular?\" Ho knows\ny fcct on of the bowels Is absolutely\n>r,d ,o\u201er\"L c ver Kee J> y<'\u00bb r liver active\na\nj M *s uilycrVi'i il e|iular y t klug laIaUvc\nJT/- C. Ayer Oo., Unwell, Mala\nAteo manufacturera of\nHAIR VIGOR.\nAlPT Q AGUE CURE.\nV W v CHERRY PECTORAL\nformal\nno secrets We publish\nm of au\nmedicines.\nSPORTING NOTES.\nThe baseball season In the Coast\nleague will begin March 9.\nThe University Of Washington is on\nthe lookout for a track coach.\nCaruthers and\nRalph Frary, Bob\nRobert Black will umpire in the North\nwest league.\nwhitman college defeated the Uni\nverglty of Idaho in a basket ball game\nrecently, 26 to 16.\n\nP\u00bbcky McFarland is alter a match\nwith Jimmie Britt or the winner of\nthe Brltt-Nelson fight.\nAt Marysville. Cal., Frank Mantell\nwas given the decision over Kid\nJack Johnson, the colored heavy\nweight, has agreed to meet Tommy\nBurns in London.\nFarmer at the end of the 20th round,\n\"Kid\" nulen, will captain the Spokane\nNorthwestern league team this year,\nWilliam Hulen, better known as\nRoy Shaw, the North Yakima base\nball player, has signed his contract\nwith the Pittsburg National league\nteam.\nPortland golfers defeated the golf\ners from Tacoma Saturday afternoon\nin 9 out of the 11 individual matches\nplayed.\nGotch at any time.\nDr. Roller, the big Seattle wrst\nler, has issued a statement that he Is\nready and willing to take on Frank\nThe University of Oregon promises\nto have a fast set of distances, five\nfreshmen in a five-mile relay covering\nthe distance in 24:36.\nJoe Pearson, perhaps tue greatest\nathlete ever turned out by the state\n0 f Washington, will return to athletics\nthis spring at Spokane.\nAurelio Herrera, the Mexican pugil\nist, of Bakersfield, Cal., was accident\nally shot in the leg by his partner,\nUaldy Wilson, recently.\nJohn S. Boa, secretary-manager of\nthe Western Boosters' Trapshooting\nassociation, announces that Butte is to\nhave a big trap tourney this year.\nAt the Park Square track, Boston,\nSaturday, Major Taylor beat Joe Fog\nler in two straight heats of a match\nbicycle race. Distance one mile and\none-half a mile.\nWith the arrival of Coach Kiesel at\nPullman, track athletics at W. S. C.\nhave taken on new life, and a big\nbunch of students are out training for\nthe various events.\nAbe Attell, the featherweight Cham\npion of America, Friday practically\nknocked out Ed Kelly, the \"Buffalo\nnewsboy,\" in the seventh round of a\nscheduled 20-round bout at Frisco.\nw. A. Hoagland of Auburn, N. Y.,\nwon the six-day walking match which\nended In Kansas City Saturday, hav\ning covered 280 miles in 62 hours,\nthus retains the world's championship.\nHo\nTrack Manager Ralph Easter of the\nUniversity of Washington is confident\nthat Washington will win the three\ncornered track meet between Wash\nington, Oregon and Idaho this spring.\nS. Metzger, chosen as head coach of\nthe University of Pennsylvania foot\nball team for the season of 1908, is in\nthe lookout for\nthe northwest on\navailable football material for the\nUniversity of Pennsylvania.\nForrest Smithson of Portland smash\ned another world's record in hurdle\nracing recently, running the 6U yards\nhurdles in 7 4-6 seconrs, 2-5 second\nbetter than the old record.\nat Trenton, N. J.\nAt the annual convention of the in\ntercollegiate association of amateur\nathletics in New York recently it was\ndecided that Pennsylvania, as holder\nof the intercollegiate track-field cham\nThe race\nwas run\npionships, was entitled to the next\nmeet.\nLouis Orsie, the crack 145-pound\nboxer at the S. A, A. C.. winner in a\nlong series of amateur contests at the\nclub, mostly by the knockout route,\nhas been protested by the Multnomah\nclub of Portland on the ground of al\nleged professionalism.\nThe six-day roller race at Lewiston\nclose Saturday night with\nConnell and Hensley\ncame to a\nout a victor, as\nare tied for first place, with a record\nof three heats each to their credit. The\ntie will be decided by another heat,\nwhich will be arranged for next week.\nMl!\nTO NEW NINE-HOUR LAW FOR\n\u2022TELEGRAPH OPERATORS.\nRailroad Magnates Plead Poverty and\nTell of Many Idle Cars, but Predict\nReturn of Trade and Prosperity in\nSpring\u2014Many Small Offices to Be\nClosed\u2014Many More Operators.\nWashington, March 2.\u2014American\nrailways have made arrangements to\ncomply March 4 with the provisions of\nthe \"nine-hour law.\" The observation\nof the law will mean the employment\nby railroad companies of several thou\nsand additional operators and the\nclosing of a large number of small\nstations on the principal systems. Dis\ncontinuing of railway service at many\npoints, it is thought, will cause at\nleast temporary inconvenience to the\ntraveling and shipping public. In or-1\nder to reduce operating expenses,\n\nwhich now seems necessary, the oper\nating officials of the railroads believe\nthat this is the only way that they\npossibly can meet the situation with\nwhich they are confronted. The law\nrequires employment of an extra oper\nator when the work requires more\nthan nine hours, and Is designed to\nsafeguard lives of passengers and 1\ntrainmen.\nDuring the hearing of applications\nfor an extension of the nine-hour law\nby the interestate commerce commis\nsion, some astonishing statements\nwere made by the operating officials\nof important railways. A good many\nrailroads, owing to a reduction in the\nrevenues and to their inability to com-1\nmand the cash necessary*to meet their\npayrolls, have been forced, during the\nlast four months, almost to the point\nof asking for receivers. In the opin\nion of railway officials expressed at\nthe hearing under oath and in private\nconversation this condition does not\nseem to have been due to the enforce\nment of regulative laws or to the In\ncapacity of railway management. Most\nof the railroad officials attribute the\ndifficulty to the unfortunate banking\nsituation which developed last Sep\ntember. The railways did not feel the\nstringency in money until about the\nfirst of November. In fact, the month\nof October was one of the best in the\nhistory of the business of American\nrailways.\nSlump Sudden and Violent.\nH. U. Mudge, vice president and 1\ngeneral manager of the Rock Island\nsystem, said: \"We were plunged from\nprosperity to adversity. A year ago\nour system could not handle the traffic\noffered us. Today we have a 1,000 idle\ncars. Five months ago we suffered\nfrom a congestion of freight; now we\nsuffer from a congestion of empty\ncars.\"\nWhat is true of one road is true of\nscores of other roads. One railroad\nofficial ventured the statement that in\nthe country today there are 400,000\nidle freight cars, and one line which\nhe instances was declared to be haul\ning empty cars backward and forward\nbecause it had not yard room or sid\nings to accommodate them.\nExpect Quick Recovery.\nNot a single official of a single rail\nroad line who appeared before the\ncommission, however, expressed the\nbelief that the present industrial de\npression would be lasting. In the tes\ntimony of nearly every witness before\nthe commission there was a note of\nconfidence because near, y every one\nof them practically believed that the\nstringency in the money market from\nwhich the country has suffered is not\ndue to fundamental causes. They point\nout that the crops last year were good\nthat prices were excellent; that indus\ntrial enterprises throughout the coun\ntry were flourishing. It was merely\nthe inability to command ready casu\nand the hoarding of money by panic -1\nstricken individuals which produced\nso suddenly the remarkable depression\nfrom which all have suffered.\nThey practically uniformly express\nconfidence that the return of prosper\nIty will be almost as sudden as was\nthe coming of adversity, and in their\narguments as to the enforcement of\nthe nine-hour law they pointed out to\nthe commission that such a return of\nprosperity might seriously embarrass\nthem in complying with the law. be\nit would render it difficult to\ncause\ncommand the services of competent\noperators in sufficient numbers to\nmeet the needs of prosperous condi\ntions.\nWith four or five exceptions, no 1m\nportant railroads of the country have\nindicated an intention to reduce the\nwages of their employes. As Chair\nFew Reduce Wages.\nman Knapp of the interstate commerce\ncommission expressed It: \"So far as\nI am informed, there is no concerted\naction on the part of the American\nrailway companies to reduce wages,\nInstances of an intention to change\nthe scale of wages have been given,\nbut they can be said to be in no sense\ngeneral.\"\nGENERAL NEWS ITEMS.\nThe city election at Seattle last Tues\nday proved to be the most overwhelm\ning republican landslide in the hisory\nof the municipality.\nThe secretary of commerce and labor\nhas issued a sweeping order to a loom\nmeroe or immigration inspectors in\ncharge,directing them to confer with\nthe police in their respective jurisdic-1\ntiens, with a view of securing \"coop-1\neration of the police in an effort to rid\nthe country of alien anarchists and\ncriminals falling within the law relat\nmg to deportation.\nStnyvesaut Fish has been forced from\nthe directorship of the Illinois railroad\nand Harrimau was blocked in his\nscheme to ratify the purchase of small\ner roads.\nCongressman W. L. Jones of Wash-1\nin g ton may introduce a resolution giv\ning full authorityto the government to\ninvestigate and proceed in the federal\ncourts to determine whether the .North\nern Pacific has compiled with the\nterms of the federal land grant act.\nJohn H. Murphy .general counsel for\nhe Western Federation of Miners and\nalso general counsel for the Brother\nr T Ai, A\nhood of Locomotive hiremeu, died\nI Tuesday of oousnmptionat his home in\nI Denver.\nThursday, April 30. and Friday May\n1, have been set for the days of the\neighth annual tri-state interscholastic\ntrack meet and declamation contest, j\nheld at the invitation of V\\ hitman col\nlege, at Walla Walla,\nWashington Men Honored.\nWashington has been honored by\ntwo appointments in the organization\nof the National Guard association of\nthe United States. General Charles\nDick of Ohio has announced that Gen\neral James A. Drain, formerly clerk of\nSpokane county, is reappointed as\nchairman of the executive committee,\nand Adjutant General Ortis Hamilton\nretains his position as a member of the\ncommittee on naval, militia and sea\ncoast defense.\nIt is said that if William A. Taft\nsucceeds to the presidency of the\nUnited States he will make Drain sec\nretary of war. Drain and Taft are\nclose personal friends, and Taft in\nthe past has done all he could to favor\nDrain.\nIntimidation Charged.\nWashington, Feb. 28.\u2014That the\nSanta Fe Railroad company intimi\ndates its telegraphers, by threats of\ndischarge. Into writing and signing\nletters repudiating him as their rep\nresentative. is the charge made by\nH. B. Perham, president of the Order\n0 f R a fiway Telegraphers. He is fight\nj ng the battles of the men in the nine\nhour-law hearing before the interstate\ncommerce commission,\nATEMPERANCE WORKER\njays Pc-ru-na is a Valuable Nerve and\nBlood Remedy.\nm\ni[\n\n\u00df\nl\nL\nBrooklyn, N. Y., is president of the\n\n\n\u2022ft\nm\n\u25a0v\nm\n\nMISS BESSIE FAgRELL\nMiss Bessie Farrell, 1011 Third Ave.,\nYoung People's Christian Temperance\nAssociation. She writes:\n\"Peruna is certainly a valuable nerve\nand blood remedy, calculated to build\nup the broken down health of worn out\nwarnen. 1 have found by personal ex\npenenc\u00a9 that it acts lisa wonderlul re\n\"\u00bb\u00abr of 03t \u00ab'fenj\u00e7th, a8sl tlng\nstomach to assimilate and digest the\nfood, and building up worn out tiss